---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How often should I get tested for STIs?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The frequency depends on your risk factors. Most medical guidelines recommend annual testing if you are sexually active. Those with multiple partners or those engaging in higher-risk activities might benefit from testing every 3 to 6 months."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the most effective form of contraception?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Long-Acting Reversible Contraceptives (LARCs) like the hormonal or copper IUD and the birth control implant are the most effective forms of reversible contraception, with success rates over 99%."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Is pull-out an effective method to prevent pregnancy?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "While better than no method at all, the pull-out method is generally considered unreliable due to the presence of sperm in pre-ejaculate and the high potential for human error. It also offers no protection against STIs."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What constitutes enthusiastic consent?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Enthusiastic consent goes beyond just the absence of a 'no'. It's an active, clear, and voluntary agreement to engage in specific sexual activity, where all parties are eager and excited to participate."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "When should I see a doctor about sexual health concerns?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You should see a doctor if you experience unusual discharge, sores, pain during sex, unexpected bleeding, or if you simply want to discuss testing, contraception, or fertility. It's also important to have routine check-ups based on age and activity."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<SiteLayout
  site="nookienook"
  title="The Comprehensive Guide to Sexual Health | The Nookie Nook"
  description="An evidence-based, inclusive guide to sexual health, covering anatomy, STIs, contraception, consent, and holistic well-being."
  canonical="https://thenookienook.com/sexual-health-guide"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>The Comprehensive Guide to Sexual Health</h1>
      <p>Your evidence-based, judgment-free resource for navigating bodies, pleasure, and well-being.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Welcome to your definitive guide to sexual health. Here at The Nookie Nook, we believe that understanding your body, knowing your rights, and communicating effectively are the cornerstones of a healthy, fulfilling sexual life. This guide is designed to be authoritative yet accessible, providing science-first information without shame or stigma.</p>

      <p>Whether you're exploring <a href="/sites/nookienook/pleasure-anatomy-guide">anatomy basics</a>, seeking clarity on <a href="/sites/nookienook/sti-testing-guide">STI prevention</a>, or looking to navigate the complex world of <a href="/sites/nookienook/contraception-comparison">contraception</a>, you'll find reliable, inclusive information here.</p>

      <h2>Understanding Anatomy</h2>
      <p>A healthy relationship with sexuality starts with a clear understanding of human anatomy. Recognizing the proper terms for body parts empowers you to communicate better with partners and healthcare providers. It's crucial to understand that bodies come in a wide variety of shapes, sizes, and configurations, all of which are normal.</p>
      <p>For a detailed breakdown of erogenous zones and the arousal response cycle, explore our <a href="/sites/nookienook/pleasure-anatomy-guide">Anatomy & Pleasure Guide</a>.</p>

      <h2>STI Prevention & Testing</h2>
      <p>Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs) are extremely common, and getting tested is a normal part of healthcare. Many STIs are asymptomatic, meaning you can have one without knowing it. Regular testing, open communication with partners, and the use of barrier methods (like condoms and dental dams) are key to prevention.</p>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Testing Guidelines</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Annually:</strong> Recommended for most sexually active adults.</li>
          <li><strong>Every 3-6 Months:</strong> Recommended for individuals with multiple partners or engaging in higher-risk activities.</li>
          <li><strong>Upon Symptoms:</strong> Seek testing immediately if you notice unusual discharge, sores, or pain.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Learn more about window periods and specific tests in our <a href="/sites/nookienook/sti-testing-guide">Complete STI Testing Guide</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Navigating Contraception</h2>
      <p>Choosing the right contraception is a highly personal decision influenced by health history, lifestyle, and future family planning goals. From Long-Acting Reversible Contraceptives (LARCs) like the IUD and implant to daily pills, barrier methods, and <a href="/sites/nookienook/fertility-window-calculator">fertility awareness</a>, the options are diverse.</p>
      <p>Compare methods side-by-side using our <a href="/sites/nookienook/contraception-comparison">Contraception Comparison Tool</a> to find what might work best for you.</p>

      <h2>Consent & Communication</h2>
      <p>Consent is the foundation of all healthy sexual encounters. It is not just the absence of "no," but the presence of an enthusiastic, ongoing, and reversible "yes." Effective communication involves articulating boundaries, expressing desires, and listening to your partner.</p>
      <p>Dive deeper into the enthusiastic consent model in our <a href="/sites/nookienook/consent-communication-guide">Guide to Consent & Sexual Communication</a> or assess your current dynamic with the <a href="/sites/nookienook/relationship-health-check">Relationship Health Assessment</a>.</p>

      <h2>Debunking Common Myths</h2>
      <p>Misinformation about sex is rampant. Whether it's the belief that you can't get pregnant during your period or that STIs always present clear symptoms, myths can lead to risky decisions and unnecessary anxiety.</p>
      <p>Test your knowledge and separate fact from fiction with our <a href="/sites/nookienook/sexual-health-myths">Myth vs. Fact Quiz</a>.</p>

      <h2>When to See a Doctor</h2>
      <p>Medical professionals are there to help, not judge. It's important to seek care for routine screenings, when starting a new relationship, or if you experience symptoms like pain, unusual bleeding, or discomfort.</p>
      <p>If you're unsure how to approach these conversations, our <a href="/sites/nookienook/guide-talking-to-doctor">Guide to Talking to Your Doctor</a> provides actionable tips on self-advocacy and finding sex-positive providers.</p>

      <h2>The Mind-Body Connection</h2>
      <p>Sexual health isn't purely physical; it's deeply intertwined with mental health. Stress, anxiety, trauma, and depression can all significantly impact libido, arousal, and overall sexual satisfaction. Addressing mental health is a vital component of holistic sexual well-being.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="related-section card">
      <h2>Related Guides & Tools</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/sti-testing-guide">Complete STI Testing Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/contraception-comparison">Contraception Comparison Tool</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/consent-communication-guide">Consent & Communication Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/fertility-window-calculator">Fertility Window Calculator</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/sexual-health-myths">Myth vs. Fact Quiz</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/guide-talking-to-doctor">How to Talk to Your Doctor</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/pleasure-anatomy-guide">Anatomy & Pleasure Guide</a></li>
        <li><a href="/sites/nookienook/relationship-health-check">Relationship Health Assessment</a></li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>
  <script is:inline>
    // Placeholder for any pillar page interactivity if needed in the future
  </script>
  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .hero p { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.2rem; }

    .content-section { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
    .content-section h2 { font-size: 1.8rem; margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; color: var(--accent-color); }
    .content-section p { margin-bottom: 1.2rem; font-size: 1.1rem; line-height: 1.7; }
    .content-section a { color: var(--accent-color); text-decoration: underline; }
    .content-section a:hover { color: var(--text-primary); }

    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 2rem; margin: 2rem 0; }
    .card h3 { margin-top: 0; color: var(--text-primary); font-size: 1.4rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .card ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
    .card li { margin-bottom: 0.8rem; }

    .related-section { margin-top: 4rem; }
    .related-section h2 { margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.6rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; text-align: center; }
    .related-section ul { list-style: none; padding: 0; display: grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(250px, 1fr)); gap: 1rem; }
    .related-section li { background: var(--bg-color); padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); text-align: center; transition: border-color 0.2s; }
    .related-section li:hover { border-color: var(--accent-color); }
    .related-section a { color: var(--text-primary); text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; display: block; }
    .related-section a:hover { color: var(--accent-color); }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>
